		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Use case</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>A <b>use case</b> in <a href="/wiki/Software_engineering" title="Software engineering">software engineering</a> and <a href="/wiki/Systems_engineering" title="Systems engineering">systems engineering</a> is a description of a system’s behaviour as it responds to a request that originates from outside of that system. In other words, a use case describes "who" can do "what" with the system in question. The use case technique is used to capture a system's behavioral requirements by detailing scenario-driven threads through the <a href="/wiki/Functional_requirement" title="Functional requirement">functional requirements</a>.</p>
